	<li id="comment-1696">
	<p>Such a great example for designers and developers new to CSS. Often times, the solution requires one to look at objects in a more dynamic way. For instance, we immediately think of the percentage bar expanding. But from a practical CSS standpoint, we have to look at it as this background image being repositioned.</p>
<p>I did a pie chart for a client in much the same way. I created a large image with 5% incremental pie charts spanned evenly and horizontally. So, I had 20 charts to display 100 different percentage possibilities. If a value was something like 35%, the chart background-position would be adjusted to &#8220;-7 x chartWidth.&#8221; It worked out nicely.
</p>
	<p><cite>Comment by <a href='http://www.dirtysouthbmx.com' rel='external nofollow'>Colin</a> &#8212; August 16, 2006 @ <a href="#comment-1696">12:24 am</a></cite> </p>
