	<p>For those needing help with the maths:</p>
<p>If the image bar image is 250px wide and is half/half colored/blank then to represent 37%:</p>
<p>(125/100)*(100-37) = 78.75</p>
<p>In words; image width divided by 100 to give is width of one percent multiplied by 100 minus the percentage we want to represent.</p>
<p>From that you should be able to figure out the details yourself.</p>
<p>One suggestion I would make is adding a title attribute so that users can mouse over the bar to get the percentage as a number appearing in a tooltip; it&#8217;s all very well having the alt text there but being an able user I don&#8217;t want to have to look at source code to find out the exact percentage being represented. </p>
<p>If you are using this alongside a text representation of the percentage then alt text is not required. A screen reader would read out the text representation the the alt text from the visual representation which could be confusing. </p>
<p>Indeed on this page the bar given as an example lacks a title attribute and the alt attribute is blank which is quite bad considering the way the sentence above is worded in such a way as to make the image a required part of the content.
</p>
	<p><cite>Comment by <a href='http://www.binarytales.co.uk' rel='external nofollow'>Jon (Different to one above)</a> &#8212; August 20, 2006 @ <a href="#comment-1804">3:50 pm</a></cite> </p>
	</li>

	<li id="comment-1807">
	<p>you could use the technique in this article:</p>
